The Problem before the sprint system, was that — I was not getting any new insights from tracking the 23 odd variables everyday, and, I was getting tired and burned just tracking so many of them. I was also spending so much time and cognitive energy on filling them, that it delayed my sleep time, and caused me to wake up later (which is one of my important metrics). So, I figured, that, I needed to reduce focus, to only the key tasks I needed to get done, in order to meet the outcome task I was looking for. 


So basically, from the 145 days of tracking daily tasks, I realized that the few metrics that contributed most to my success, were: 
1. Early Wake up time — I realized that in order to beat my IP, I needed to wake up early, and get a strong morning routine in, that will help regulate me before I do any of my tasks. This is crucial so that I feel ‘good’ and ‘relaxed’ and not reacting to anything from the outside world,  before I can get my peace. So, it because important to wake up earlier. Also realizing that, I need more and more and more time in the morning, to do my routine, to do my IP attack, I realized that waking up way earlier was the way to go.  So I decided to track how much earlier I can wake up. Based on current morning requirements, I needed to wake up at 4:30 thats what im tracking towards. 
2. Morning Routine — Realized that I needed to regulate. 3 important regulatory activities were meditation, reading and visualizing for the day. Decided to club into 1 (because they serve the same overarching purpose), and track it as such. 
3. IP Attack — Very crucial. I needed to identify (through my visualization / planning activity from the mining routine) and attack my IP task first thing in the morning, so that I can have a large Identity defining load off my back in the morning. Doing this in the morning came up as important indicator for success. 
4. Gym — I just must go to the gym everyday, and train myself for better fitness. I learnt over time that physical fitness translated to mental fires, and I am now sure it will boost my overall mood and help me achieve my target task. 
5. Anthropic Progress — finally, my target task. The outcome I am looking for. This is most curricula task I need to get done at the moment, and the other 4 are enablers for me to get this outcome. 



I want to note a theory I have not noted before - -one that gave birth to the sprints. 

There are always enabler tasks, and an outcome tasks. I should probably not call them tasks. Hmmm — I should call them indicatory maybe? 

Okay — there are enablers and targets. Let’s just call them that. 

Enablers are the activities that help me build up to achieving a target. The ‘process’ so to speak. These are the activities, if done correctly, will help me achieve the ‘target outcome / result / task’. I cannot just call them ‘process’ and ‘result’, because, often times, the ‘result’ is also a ‘process’. For example, right now, my  desired ‘result’ is that I do the anthropic work everyday for 120 minutes. And to ‘enable’ this, I need the other 4 in place to do so. Makes sense? 

The outcome of Observation: Enablers that work: 
So, the outcome of the initial observation phase, was that, in order for me to get to whatever target outcome I needed, I need to have certain enablers. I have identified these enablers, through the observation phase. Now, during observation, I had the ‘target’ of ‘not smoking’ / ‘reading’ / ‘exercising’ / ‘meditating’…

The observation phase always must start with targets only. Because, the user likely does not yet know what the enablers are, that can help them achieve those targets. With observation, over time, enablers start to emerge through user analysis, and of course, the CPO analysis reports generated by SelfPM. Once they start to emerge, users(I want to start calling them seekers from now on — because they ‘seek’ a target) can start tracking these enablers, and experiment to see which ones have the most impact on their targets. 


For me, I noticed that the enablers with the most influence, were waking early, IP attack, routine and gym, and so, I am tracking those as the enablers, towards my target of Anthropic Prep. 

The sprint helps me in 2 ways. 
1. Allows me to focus on these enablers, and understand them deeply. Are they actually correct? Can they be more specific / improved? Do they work toward my target? Is there a way I can do them better? 
2. Track towards specific goals I want for my target. I NEED TO ACHIEVE MY TARGET 6/7 times a week for success. Am I able to do it? What are my blockers? How can I mitigate / prevent? 


He Outcome of Sprint / Execution: Targets that are Met 
At the end of each sprint, I want to measure the success rate of my target, and understand causal relationships with my enablers. I obviously think there will be a relationship, but im happy to learn if there isn’t. 

The more success My target shows, the better I am doing. If there is a causal relationship, it means my observation phase gave me the right results. If not,  maybe there are more enablers I have not yet discovered? I might give 3 sprints time to reach my target goal (6/7 Times) at least 1 time. If not, I will need to go back to observation, and try new metrics. Maybe. I’llm no sure yet what my next step will be if the sprint fails. I’ll have to wait to find out. But, atleast I know what success looks like. 


 Why a 7-day sprint? Why not 14?— 7 day sprints because they allow me to execute over the course of a week — which is generally the unit of time over which I judge my ability to execute anything. I model my life based on weeks, based on the 7 habits of highly effective people, and it gives me enough understanding and feedback on how I work on all the different possible environments (each day of the week might be different based on my work schedule, cricket practice, weekends, etc, but they are the same every week. So, if I can understand how I perform across a week, I can replicate it across). Ideally, I want to try this over the smallest unit of time, which I can replicate over and over again. Right now, that unit of time, which allows the other interactions in my life (work, cricket, mom, friends, etc), is a week. Every Sunday, I get time to analyze, assess, and plan for the week ahead based on my learnings from the previous. 
  - Why the dashboard grid layout?
— It allows me to see my progress in detail, on the face of my interaction with SelfPM. Before, in daily task tracker, I can ill out my daily activities without seeing the dashboard — I m solved of some result orientation, because I can’t see it, or, there is some friction for me to want to go see it. Not here. Since this is execution phase, I almost want there to be a fire up my butt, so I know where ei am, and where I need to go. The dashboard, along with the color scheme, helps me see and achieve it. 
  - Why today/yesterday editing only?
— Ideally, I only want to allow editing of today’s activities, because it allows for the best quality responses, because the Day is fresh in my memory. Even better would be if seeker fills in each note as and when they ‘complete’ the boundaries of that enabler/ target. But, factoring in time constraints, I allow it to be the whole day. I also allow next day — with the introduction of sprints, there is a judgement introduced back into the system. Some shame possibly, if a target/ enabler was not completed. The same day can be tough for the seeker to freely admit the details and nuances of their failure. Its okay. This is why they might be able to do it the next day. With a more open mind, tuned for reflection and feedback, than guilt / shame. I accept. I predict the next day will most likely be used only for failed tasks / Highest IP tasks, but either way, im okay to give the seeker this grace. I think it will result in stronger notes and insight. 
  - Why notes per metric vs. one daily note?
— obviously for content quality. Nots per enabler / target allow 2 things. 1. Allows the user to bee more targeted in their thought — thinksepcifically and document how you performed on this enabler / target and document. 2. Also allows the system to analyze and find patterns at a later time. Easier if classified into buckets per task. 3. The user, since they naturally progress from observation (daily task tracking - -where they enter yes /no / dropdown, and then fill a note per task) to Execution (sprint), they will like, and be used to the result of enabler / target + note filling mechanism. I want to retain this familiarity. 


As I say this, I imagine, that I will also benefit from adding a ‘general’ notes section at the bottom. Same 2500 characters, just a general note that allows the seeker to note any other factors / observations from the day. Since the seeker sacrifices tracking many other potential enablers / metrics to track the sprint selections (lets call them gems — collection of targets and enablers chosen in a particular sprint, usually derived from the observation phase), they might miss out on recording / observing if there is progress on any other. The presence of this ‘general’ note entry will allow the seeker to ‘continue’ observation’, as they focus on specific execution of the sprint gems. This will likely give good insight to guide future sprints, especially if the current enablers fail to product target result. Then, seekers may look to the general notes to observe and identify new potential enablers/ gems. 


User Story: 

Before Sprints, I was just tracking ALL my possible metrics everyday. I was honestly getting tired of it little. I wasn’t seeing ‘progress’. I guess an insight im learning from this is to not keep seekers in the observation phase for too long. I must be quicker to iterate between observation and execution (sprint) phases. Maybe 3 weeks? And then create gems for a sprint? Anyway I have the ‘general note’ area to capture additional context. This will aid In informing gems. 

Anyway, now that I have sprints, I am ably able to think in terms of activities I need to get done everyday. Now that I think about it, another enabler could be for me to think /. Read my mission statement everyday. I want to be reminded of my mission. Why I am doing this. The purpose. I want to join anthropic, the world’s best AI company, for respect. To actually be good. That’s what it is. I want to actually be good at something. And I think the best way to do that is to work at the best company, surrounded by the smartest people. This mission statement should be on my selfPM Sprint dashboard. I should likely incorporate this for other users as well. 

Sprints help me see a definitive finish line for my enablers and targets, and help me plan the urgency with which I need to do them. 

Im thinking now, maybe I should break down my notes — how I did today, vs, my plan for tomorrow? Everyday, when I account for a particular gem, I also want to plan the next iteration of it (tomorrow). May not be required for the ’same task’ (like morning routine — which I do the same things everyday, more or less same time), but more so I guess for subjective tasks — if they have not already been planned. 

Or, more so, if I fail a particular day, I am required to give a substantial plan for how I am going to execute it the next iteration successfully. This is what I need to do. I need to give a plan on how I will execute it successfully. What time I will do it, what place, what enablers I will use (even if the gem in question is an enabler itself — it’s totally possible to have enablers for an enabler. A nested enabler if you will). 

I will incorporate this in the next sprint. 
